                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Charmed pet damage doesn't appear to scale on anything even remotely related to the scale of the creature's 'normal' max hit.  Let me show you what I mean:
<br />

<br />
Charm a Dragorn Peon in Dranik's Hollows.  This mob hits for ~360 normally, and hits for about 220 when charmed.  This isn't half bad.
<br />

<br />
Charm a Baleful Stoneworker in The Ruined City of Dranik. This mob hits for ~600 normally and like... 245 when charmed. WTF?   This is a 65% or so increase in pre-charm damage, and a roughly 12% increase in post charm damage.  
<br />

<br />
This is not acceptable.  Charming a more dangerous pet has to result in a significant- increase in damage.  That damage -needs- to be linked in some meaningful way to the pets pre-charm damage.
<br />

<br />
It rapidly becomes clear that Nanyea's statement that the post-charm damage tables were set to 50% of pre-charm is incorrect - rather, it seems that the post charm damage tables were arbitrarily set to some number in the low-mid 200's, regardless of the mob's precharm damage.
<br />

<br />
I am not pleased.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
